1. Eager Loading vs Lazy Loading (Conceptual Foundation)
Let’s visualize the difference using a simple diagram (no images, just clear text-based flow):
EAGER LOADING (Traditional / Default)
--------------------------------------
User opens app
|
v
[ Download EVERYTHING: Home + Dashboard + Admin + Reports + Settings ]
|
v
[ Parse & Execute ALL modules ]
|
v
User sees Home Page (but paid the cost of downloading Admin, Reports, Settings too!)LAZY LOADING
--------------------------------------
User opens app
|
v
[ Download ONLY: Home module (small) ]
|
v
User sees Home Page FAST
|
v
User clicks "Dashboard" link
|
v
[ Angular Router detects navigation -> fetches Dashboard chunk NOW ]
|
v
User sees Dashboard (small delay, but only paid for what they used)Theoretical Explanation
In a Single Page Application (SPA), your code is compiled into what are called bundles (or chunks). Without lazy loading, Angular’s build tool (esbuild/Webpack under the hood of the Angular CLI) creates one massive main.js file containing your whole app.
With lazy loading, Angular’s Router becomes aware that certain routes correspond to separate files that haven’t been downloaded yet. It uses dynamic import() statements (a native JavaScript feature) to fetch those files only when needed. This is the foundational browser feature that makes all of this possible — Angular is essentially orchestrating native ES Module dynamic imports for you, tied to your routing configuration.

2. How Angular Bundles Code: Understanding Chunks
When you build an Angular app using ng build, the CLI analyzes your routing configuration. Any route that uses loadChildren or loadComponent (we'll explain both below) is automatically split into its own lazy chunk — a separate .js file.
Build Output Example:
----------------------------------
main.js --> Core app shell, always loaded
polyfills.js --> Browser compatibility code
styles.css --> Global styles
chunk-DASHBOARD.js --> Only loaded when user visits /dashboard
chunk-ADMIN.js --> Only loaded when user visits /admin
chunk-REPORTS.js --> Only loaded when user visits /reportsWhy this matters (Theory)
Each chunk is fetched via an HTTP request only when triggered. This means your Time to Interactive (TTI) and First Contentful Paint (FCP) — two crucial performance metrics — improve dramatically because the browser has far less to process upfront.

3. Basic Route-Level Lazy Loading
This is the classic and most well-known pattern: lazy loading an entire NgModule tied to a route.
Step 1: Create a Feature Module
// dashboard/dashboard.module.ts
import { NgModule } from '@angular/core';
import { CommonModule } from '@angular/common';
import { RouterModule, Routes } from '@angular/router';
import { DashboardComponent } from './dashboard.component';const routes: Routes = [
{ path: '', component: DashboardComponent }
];
@NgModule({
declarations: [DashboardComponent],
imports: [
CommonModule,
RouterModule.forChild(routes) // forChild registers routes WITHIN this lazy module
]
})
export class DashboardModule {}
Step 2: Reference It Lazily in the Main Router
// app-routing.module.ts
import { NgModule } from '@angular/core';
import { RouterModule, Routes } from '@angular/router';const routes: Routes = [
{
path: 'dashboard',
loadChildren: () =>
import('./dashboard/dashboard.module').then(m => m.DashboardModule)
}
];
@NgModule({
imports: [RouterModule.forRoot(routes)],
exports: [RouterModule]
})
export class AppRoutingModule {}
Theoretical Breakdown (Line by Line)

• loadChildren accepts a function that returns a Promise.

• import('./dashboard/dashboard.module') is a dynamic import — a native browser/JS feature that fetches a module asynchronously instead of bundling it at compile time with a static import statement at the top of the file.

• .then(m => m.DashboardModule) extracts the actual DashboardModule class from the imported file, because dynamic imports return an object containing all the named exports of that file.

• Angular’s Router waits for this promise to resolve before activating the route, and caches the loaded module so it isn’t re-fetched on subsequent visits.
This pattern is still valid today, but Angular has since introduced a leaner, more modern alternative — Standalone Components — which we’ll explore next.

4. Standalone Component Lazy Loading (Modern Angular)
Since Angular 14+ (and strongly encouraged from Angular 17+ onward), you don’t need NgModules at all. You can lazy load a single component directly.
// app.routes.ts
import { Routes } from '@angular/router';export const routes: Routes = [
{
path: 'dashboard',
loadComponent: () =>
import('./dashboard/dashboard.component').then(c => c.DashboardComponent)
},
{
path: 'reports',
loadComponent: () =>
import('./reports/reports.component').then(c => c.ReportsComponent)
}
];
// dashboard.component.ts
import { Component } from '@angular/core';
import { CommonModule } from '@angular/common';@Component({
selector: 'app-dashboard',
standalone: true,
imports: [CommonModule],
template: `<h2>Welcome to your Dashboard</h2>`
})
export class DashboardComponent {}
Theoretical Explanation
loadComponent works exactly like loadChildren, except it skips the "wrapper module" step entirely. This is possible because standalone components declare their own dependencies (via the imports array in the @Component decorator) instead of relying on an NgModule to declare them.
Why this is “advanced” despite looking simpler: It removes an entire architectural layer (NgModules), reduces boilerplate, and produces smaller, more granular chunks — meaning the browser can cache and fetch things more efficiently.
Lazy Loading Nested Child Routes (Standalone Style)
export const routes: Routes = [
{
path: 'dashboard',
loadComponent: () =>
import('./dashboard/dashboard.component').then(c => c.DashboardComponent),
children: [
{
path: 'analytics',
loadComponent: () =>
import('./dashboard/analytics/analytics.component').then(c => c.AnalyticsComponent)
},
{
path: 'settings',
loadComponent: () =>
import('./dashboard/settings/settings.component').then(c => c.SettingsComponent)
}
]
}
];Flow Diagram: Nested Lazy Loading
-----------------------------------------------
/dashboard (loads DashboardComponent chunk)
|
+-- /dashboard/analytics (loads AnalyticsComponent chunk ONLY when visited)
|
+-- /dashboard/settings (loads SettingsComponent chunk ONLY when visited)Each child route is its own independent chunk. Visiting /dashboard does NOT download /dashboard/analytics — that only happens when the user actually clicks into Analytics.

5. Preloading Strategies
Lazy loading alone can sometimes feel “too lazy” — users might experience a small delay/flicker the first time they click a link because the chunk is being fetched right at that moment.
Preloading solves this: Angular loads the lazy chunks silently in the background after the initial app has loaded, so that by the time the user clicks, the chunk is already cached.
Timeline Diagram: PreloadAllModules Strategy
---------------------------------------------------------
t=0s App starts, Home chunk loads
t=0.5s User sees Home page (fast!)
t=0.6s --> Angular Router silently starts preloading
Dashboard chunk, Reports chunk, Admin chunk
in the background (low priority, doesn't block UI)
t=2s All chunks preloaded quietly
t=5s User clicks "Dashboard" --> INSTANT (already cached!)Code: Enabling Built-in Preloading
// app.config.ts (standalone app bootstrap)
import { ApplicationConfig } from '@angular/core';
import { provideRouter, withPreloading, PreloadAllModules } from '@angular/router';
import { routes } from './app.routes';export const appConfig: ApplicationConfig = {
providers: [
provideRouter(routes, withPreloading(PreloadAllModules))
]
};
Theoretical Explanation
PreloadAllModules is a built-in PreloadingStrategy class Angular ships with. Once your initial route finishes rendering, the Router iterates through your route config and triggers the dynamic imports for every lazy route — but does so using the browser's idle time, so it doesn't compete with more important initial rendering work.
This is a good default for small-to-medium apps where you expect users to eventually visit most routes. But it’s not ideal for large apps with dozens of feature modules that many users will never touch (e.g., an “Admin” section only 2% of users access). That’s where custom preloading comes in.

6. Custom Preloading Strategy (Advanced Pattern)
This is where lazy loading becomes truly “advanced.” You can write your own logic to decide which routes get preloaded and when — based on custom data flags, network conditions, or user roles.
Step 1: Mark Routes with Custom Data
export const routes: Routes = [
{
path: 'dashboard',
loadComponent: () => import('./dashboard/dashboard.component').then(c => c.DashboardComponent),
data: { preload: true } // custom flag
},
{
path: 'admin',
loadComponent: () => import('./admin/admin.component').then(c => c.AdminComponent),
data: { preload: false } // don't bother preloading — rarely visited
}
];Step 2: Write a Custom Preloading Strategy Class
// custom-preloading.strategy.ts
import { Injectable } from '@angular/core';
import { PreloadingStrategy, Route } from '@angular/router';
import { Observable, of } from 'rxjs';@Injectable({ providedIn: 'root' })
export class CustomPreloadingStrategy implements PreloadingStrategy {
preload(route: Route, load: () => Observable<any>): Observable<any> {
// Only preload if the route explicitly opts in via data.preload
if (route.data && route.data['preload']) {
console.log('Preloading:', route.path);
return load(); // triggers the actual dynamic import
}
return of(null); // skip preloading, load only on-demand
}
}
Step 3: Register It
// app.config.ts
import { provideRouter, withPreloading } from '@angular/router';
import { CustomPreloadingStrategy } from './custom-preloading.strategy';
import { routes } from './app.routes';export const appConfig: ApplicationConfig = {
providers: [
provideRouter(routes, withPreloading(CustomPreloadingStrategy))
]
};
Theoretical Breakdown

• The PreloadingStrategy interface has one method: preload(route, load).

